# {VAULT_NAME} — second-brain personal vault

This is a personal second-brain. The graph is in `notes/`. Atoms are **memories** (one experience or insight per file). Bodies are 100–400 words. Frontmatter is the contract; the `description` field is the model's first triage signal.

CLAUDE.md (alongside this file) holds session-start instructions; the rest of the vault contract is here.

The personal preset uses warmer language than the research preset; tune your own personality in `self/identity.md`.

## The verbs

Same as research, with looser application:

- `/extract <source>` — usually unused; personal capture is direct
- `/connect <note>` — link a memory to people/places/themes
- `/walk <query>` — search the graph
- `/audit <note>` — quality check (less strict than research)
- `/learn <source>` — for occasional sources you want to digest deeply (a book, a podcast)
- `/anneal --scope=...` — periodic care for the graph
- `/no-surrender <target>` — *opt-in via `surrender.enabled` in `vault.yaml` (default off).* Probe your grip on a memory or reflection. The default axes are research-oriented; adapt locally if you want to track engagement on memories — engagement is fuzzier here than for atomic claims.
- `/init` — once

## Atom contract

A **memory** lives at `notes/<kebab-case-of-the-memory>.md`:

```yaml
---
description: "One sentence of context that isn't the title"
type: memory
confidence: vivid | clear | hazy | reconstructed
created: YYYY-MM-DD
when: YYYY-MM-DD or ~range
where: "[[place-link]]" (optional)
who: ["[[person]]", ...]
themes: [tag, tag, ...]
---
```

A **life-area map** lives at `notes/_<area>.md`:

```yaml
---
description: "What this life area covers"
type: life-area-map
parent_map: "[[index]]"
---
```

## Walking conventions

- Inline links carry the weight of context. Don't pile bare wikilinks.
- Memory titles are first-person prose: "the day i noticed dad was getting older", "what i learned from the july review".
- Linking is voluntary; this isn't research. A solitary memory still has value.

## Subagent policy

Almost never. Personal capture is small-scale. Spawn only for:
- Reading a long book and extracting many memories (`/learn --deep`)
- Whole-vault sweeps (`/audit --vault`, `/anneal --scope=vault`)

